Definition 2.9. A map $f$ in a Cartesian differential category is linear when $\mathsf{D}[f]=\pi_{1}f$. Similarly, a map $A\times B\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 17.24992pt{\rightarrowfill}}% \limits^{\hbox{\scriptsize$f$}}}C$ is linear in $B$ if the following diagram commutes: $\tikzcd A\times(B\times B)\ar[dr,"1\times\pi_{1}"^{\prime}]\ar[rr,"{D_{B}[f]}"% ]&&C\\ &A\times B\ar[ur,"f"^{\prime}]$
Definition 2.4. A Cartesian differential category [2] is a Cartesian left additive category with a combinator $\mathsf{D}$, called the differential combinator, which written as an inference rule is given by: $\infer{A\times A\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 32.99968pt{% \rightarrowfill}}\limits_{\hbox{\scriptsize$\mathsf{D}[f]$}}}B}{A\allowbreak% \mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 17.24992pt{\rightarrowfill}}\limits^{\hbox{% \scriptsize$f$}}}B}$ where $\mathsf{D}[f]$ is called the derivative of $f$, and such that the following equalities hold3Note that the order of variables is different here than in [2]; here, we write the vector variable in the second component, as this more closely aligns with standard differential calculus notation.: [CDC.1] $\mathsf{D}[f+g]=\mathsf{D}[f]+\mathsf{D}[g]$ and $\mathsf{D}[0]=0$; [CDC.2] $\left\langle a,b+c\right\rangle\mathsf{D}[f]=\left\langle a,b\right\rangle% \mathsf{D}[f]+\left\langle a,c\right\rangle\mathsf{D}[f]$ and $\left\langle a,0\right\rangle\mathsf{D}[f]=0$; [CDC.3] $\mathsf{D}[1]=\pi_{1}$, $\mathsf{D}[\pi_{0}]=\pi_{1}\pi_{0}$, and $\mathsf{D}[\pi_{1}]=\pi_{1}\pi_{1}$; [CDC.4] $\mathsf{D}[\left\langle f,g\right\rangle]=\left\langle\mathsf{D}[f],\mathsf{D}% [g]\right\rangle$; [CDC.5] $\mathsf{D}[fg]=\left\langle\pi_{0}f,\mathsf{D}[f]\right\rangle\mathsf{D}[g]$; [CDC.6] $\left\langle\left\langle a,b\right\rangle,\left\langle 0,c\right\rangle\right% \rangle\mathsf{D}[\mathsf{D}[f]]=\left\langle a,c\right\rangle\mathsf{D}[f]$; [CDC.7] $\left\langle\left\langle a,b\right\rangle,\left\langle c,d\right\rangle\right% \rangle\mathsf{D}[\mathsf{D}[f]]=\left\langle\left\langle a,c\right\rangle,% \left\langle b,d\right\rangle\right\rangle\mathsf{D}[\mathsf{D}[f]]$.
Definition 2.1. A left additive category [2, Definition 1.1.1] is a category $\mathbb{X}$ such that each hom-set is a commutative monoid, with addition operation + and zero maps 0, such that composition on the left preserves the additives structure in the sense that $x(f+g)=xf+xg$ and $x0=0$. Maps $h$ which preserve the additive structure by composition on the right ($(x+y)h=xh+yh$ and $0h=0$) are called additive. A Cartesian left additive category [2, Definition 1.2.1] is a left additive category $\mathbb{X}$ which is Cartesian and such that all projection maps $\pi_{i}$ are additive2Note that this a slight variation on the definition of a Cartesian left additive category found in [2], but it is indeed equivalent..
Definition 4.4. Suppose that $\mathbb{X}\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 17.24992pt{\rightarrowfill}}% \limits^{\hbox{\scriptsize$q$}}}\mathbb{B}$ is a fibration. The dual fibration of $q$ [5, 13] is a fibration $\mathbb{X}^{\ast}\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 20.189875pt{% \rightarrowfill}}\limits^{\hbox{\scriptsize$q^{\ast}$}}}\mathbb{B}$ whose total category $\mathbb{X}^{\ast}$ has the same objects as $\mathbb{X}$ and where a map $X\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 12.0pt{\rightarrowfill}}\limits}Y$ in $\mathbb{X}^{\ast}$ is an equivalence class of spans $\tikzcd S\ar[r,"c"]\ar[d,"v"^{\prime}]&Y\\ X$ where $v$ is vertical and $c$ is Cartesian (over $q(c)$) under the equivalence relation $(v,c)\sim(v^{\prime},c^{\prime})$ when there is a vertical isomorphism $\alpha$ that makes the following diagram commute. $\tikzcd&S^{\prime}\ar[d,"\alpha"]\ar[dl,"v^{\prime}"^{\prime}]\ar[dr,"c^{% \prime}"]\\ X&S\ar[l,"v"]\ar[r,"c"^{\prime}]&Y$ To compose such spans, note that given a cospan $S\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 17.24992pt{\rightarrowfill}}\limits^{% \hbox{\scriptsize$c$}}}X^{\prime}\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 20.189875pt{% \leftarrowfill}}\limits^{\hbox{\scriptsize$v^{\prime}$}}}S^{\prime}$ with $c$ cartesian and $v^{\prime}$ vertical,that there is a cartesian arrow over $q(c)$ with codomain $S^{\prime}$, and this induces uniquely a $v^{\prime\prime}$ making the relevant square commute, and we get a span $S\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 23.12983pt{\leftarrowfill}}\limits^{\hbox{% \scriptsize$v^{\prime\prime}$}}}S^{\prime\prime}\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{% \hbox to 19.499886pt{\rightarrowfill}}\limits^{\hbox{\scriptsize$\hat{c}$}}}S^% {\prime}$ with $v^{\prime\prime}$ vertical and $\hat{c}$ cartesian; this span is used to from the composite of the spans $(v,c)(v^{\prime},c^{\prime})$. For more details, see [13]. The fibration $q^{\ast}$ is defined on objects as $q^{\ast}(A):=q(A)$, and defined on maps as $q^{\ast}(v,c):=q(X)=q(S)\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 32.99968pt{% \rightarrowfill}}\limits^{\hbox{\scriptsize$q(C)$}}}q(Y)$.
Definition 4.20. Let $\mathbb{X}$ be a Cartesian differential category. We say that $\mathbb{X}$ has a contextual linear dagger when the linear fibration is a dagger fibration $\tikzcd\widetilde{\mathsf{Lin}(\mathbb{X})}\ar[dr,"\pi"^{\prime}]\ar[rr,"{(% \underline{\leavevmode\nobreak\ })^{\dagger}}"]&&\widetilde{\mathsf{Lin}(% \mathbb{X})}^{\ast}\ar[dl,"\pi^{\ast}"]\\ &\mathbb{X}$ and each fiber category $\mathsf{Lin}(\mathbb{X})[A]$ has $\dagger$-biproducts.
Definition 4.11. A dagger fibration is given by a fibration $\mathbb{X}\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 17.24992pt{\rightarrowfill}}% \limits^{\hbox{\scriptsize$q$}}}\mathbb{B}$ with a morphism of fibrations $\mathbb{X}\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 32.93968pt{\rightarrowfill}}% \limits^{\hbox{\scriptsize$(\underline{\leavevmode\nobreak\ })^{\dagger}$}}}% \mathbb{X}^{\ast}$ such that $\tikzcd\mathbb{X}\ar[r,"(\underline{\leavevmode\nobreak\ })^{\dagger}"]\ar[dr,% "q"^{\prime}]\ar[rr,bendleft,shiftleft,"1_{\mathbb{X}}"]&\mathbb{X}^{\ast}\ar[% d,"q^{\ast}"]\ar[r,"(\underline{\leavevmode\nobreak\ })^{\dagger}"]&\mathbb{X}% ^{\ast\ast}=\mathbb{X}\ar[dl,"q"]\\ &\mathbb{B}$ and such that $\dagger$ is stationary on objects. A dagger fibration has a dagger cleavage when $(\underline{\leavevmode\nobreak\ })^{\dagger}$ sends cloven cartesian arrows to cloven cartesian arrows.
Definition 3.8. A $\dagger$-category [18] is a category $\mathbb{X}$ with a stationary on objects involution $\mathbb{X}^{\text{op}}\allowbreak\mathrel{\mathop{\hbox to 32.93968pt{% \rightarrowfill}}\limits^{\hbox{\scriptsize$(\underline{\leavevmode\nobreak\ }% )^{\dagger}$}}}\mathbb{X}$. A $\dagger$-category that also has finite biproducts $\oplus$, with projection maps $\pi_{i}$ and injection maps $\iota_{i}$, is said to have $\dagger$-biproducts [18] when $\pi_{i}^{\dagger}=\iota_{i}$ (or equivalently if $\iota^{\dagger}_{i}=\pi_{i}$).
Definition 2.20. Let $\mathcal{T}$ be a triangulated category with coproducts and $G\in\mathcal{T}$ an object in $\mathcal{T}$. Then, $\mathcal{T}$ is said to be fast generated by $G$ if $\mathcal{T}=Coprod_{n}(G[-\infty,\infty])$.
Definition 2.9. A triangulated category $\mathcal{T}$ is called regular or strongly generated if a strong generator exists.
Definition 2.7. Let $\mathcal{T}$ be a triangulated category and $G\in\mathcal{T}$ an object. The full subcategory $\langle G\rangle_{n}\subset\mathcal{T}$ is defined inductively as follows: i) $\langle G\rangle_{1}$ is the full subcategory consisting of all direct summands of finite coproducts of suspensions of $G$. ii) For $n>1$, $\langle G\rangle_{n}$ is the full subcategory consisting of all objects that are direct summand of an object $y$, where $y$ fits into a triangle $x\to y\to z$, with $x\in\langle G\rangle_{1}$ and $z\in\langle G\rangle_{n-1}$.
Definition 2.1 (Local Isomorphism). A morphism of schemes $f:X\to Y$ is a local isomorphism if every point of $X$ is contained in an open $U\subset X$ such that $f$ induces an open immersion $U\to Y$.
Definition 2.12. Let $\mathcal{T}$ be a triangulated category with $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{B}$ two subcategories of $\mathcal{T}$. Then: i) $\mathcal{A}\star\mathcal{B}$ is the full subcategory of all objects $y$ for which there exist a triangle $x\to y\to z$ with $x\in\mathcal{A}$ and $z\in\mathcal{B}$. ii) $add(\mathcal{A})$ is the full subcategory containing all finite coproducts of objects in $\mathcal{A}$. iii) If $\mathcal{T}$ is closed under coproducts, then $Add(\mathcal{A})$ is the full subcategory containing all (set-indexed) coproducts of objects in $\mathcal{A}$ iv) If $\mathcal{A}$ is also a full subcategory, then $smd(\mathcal{A})$ is the full subcategory of all direct summands of objects in $\mathcal{A}$.
Definition 2.3. Let $f:T\to S$ a morphism of schemes. A separator of $f$, or a separator through $f$, is a morphism of $S$-schemes $h:T\to E$, with $E$ separated over $S$, such that the following propreties are satisfied: i) $h$ is a quasicompact, quasiseparated, surjective local isomorphism, and ii) the diagonal morphism $\Delta_{h}$ is schematic dominant.
Definition 2.11. Let $\mathcal{T}$ be a triangulated category with coproducts, $G\in\mathcal{T}$ an object and $A<B$ integers. Then $\overline{\langle G\rangle}_{n}^{[A,B]}\subset\mathcal{T}$ is the full subcategory defined inductively as follows: i) $\overline{\langle G\rangle}_{1}^{[A,B]}$ is the full subcategory consisting of all direct summands of abritary coproducts of objects in the set $\{\Sigma^{-i}G,A\leq i\leq B\}$ . ii) $\overline{\langle G\rangle}_{n}^{[A,B]}$ is the full subcategory consisting of all objects that are direct summand of an object $y$, where $y$ fits into a triangle $x\to y\to z$, with $x\in\overline{\langle G\rangle}_{1}^{[A,B]}$ and $z\in\overline{\langle G\rangle}_{n-1}^{[A,B]}$.
Definition 3.4. Let $f:X\to Y$ be the separator and $V\subset X$ be an open affine. Define $Z_{V}$ as the closure of the set $\{x\in V;f^{-1}f(x)\neq\{x\}\}$ (the non separated points of V).
Definition 2.8. Let $G$ be an object in a triangulated category $\mathcal{T}$. Then $G$ is said to be a classical generator if $\mathcal{T}=\cup_{n=1}^{\infty}\langle G\rangle_{n}$ and a strong generator if there exists an $n\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq 1}$ with $\mathcal{T}=\langle G\rangle_{n}$.
Definition 2.13. Let $\mathcal{T}$ be a triangulated category and $\mathcal{A}$ a subcategory. Define: $\displaystyle\text{i)}\ coprod_{1}(\mathcal{A})$ $\displaystyle:=add(\mathcal{A});$ $\displaystyle coprod_{n+1}(\mathcal{A})$ $\displaystyle:=coprod_{1}(\mathcal{A})\star coprod_{n}(\mathcal{A}).$ $\displaystyle\text{ii)}\ Coprod_{1}(\mathcal{A})$ $\displaystyle:=Add(\mathcal{A});$ $\displaystyle Coprod_{n+1}(\mathcal{A})$ $\displaystyle:=Coprod_{1}(\mathcal{A})\star Coprod_{n}(\mathcal{A}).$ $\displaystyle\text{iii)}\ coprod(\mathcal{A})$ $\displaystyle:=\cup^{\infty}_{n=1}coprod_{n}(\mathcal{A}).$ $\text{iv) }Coprod(\mathcal{A})\text{ is the smallest strictly full subcategory% of }\mathcal{T}$ [assumed to have coproducts] containing $\mathcal{A}$ and satisfying $\displaystyle Add(Coprod(\mathcal{A}))\subset Coprod(\mathcal{A})$ and $\displaystyle Coprod(\mathcal{A})\star\text{Coprod}(\mathcal{A})\subset Coprod% (\mathcal{A}).$
Definition 1.1. Let $\mathbf{C}$ be any category and let ${\mathcal{G}}\subseteq\mathbf{C}$ be a set of objects. (1) We say that ${\mathcal{G}}$ jointly reflects isomorphisms if a morphism $f:X\to Y$ in $\mathbf{C}$ is an isomorphism whenever $\mathbf{C}(S,f):\mathbf{C}(S,X)\to\mathbf{C}(S,Y)$ is an isomorphism for every $S\in{\mathcal{G}}$. (Heller uses the terminology “left adequate.”) (2) A weak colimit of a diagram $D:\mathbf{I}\to\mathbf{C}$ is a cocone through which every cocone factors, not necessarily uniquely. (3) A weak colimit $W$ of $D:\mathbf{I}\to\mathbf{C}$ is ${\mathcal{G}}$-privileged if the canonical map $\operatorname*{colim}_{\alpha\in\mathcal{I}}\mathbf{C}(S,D(\alpha))\to\mathbf{% C}(S,W)$ is a bijection for every $S\in{\mathcal{G}}$. (4) For an ordinal $\beta$, we say that ${\mathcal{G}}$ is $\beta$-bounded if every diagram $D:\beta\to\mathbf{C}$ has a ${\mathcal{G}}$-privileged weak colimit. (5) We say that ${\mathcal{G}}$ is left cardinally bounded, or just bounded, if it is $\beta$-bounded for each sufficiently large regular cardinal $\beta$.
Definition 3.10. Define a graph of groups $\Gamma$ with object set $[2,\kappa)$, edge set $\{y_{\alpha}^{\beta}:\beta\to\alpha\mid\break\alpha\neq\beta\in[2,\kappa)\}$, vertex group $G_{\alpha}$ free on $\alpha$ generators, for $\alpha\in[2,\kappa)$, and involution $y_{\alpha}^{\beta}\mapsto y_{\beta}^{\alpha}$. The edge group $G_{y^{\beta}_{\alpha}}$ is just $G_{\min(\beta,\alpha)}$. The edge morphism $\mu_{y^{\beta}_{\alpha}}:G_{\min(\beta,\alpha)}\to G_{\beta}$ is the natural inclusion. Let $Z=\Pi_{1}\Gamma$. Next, define a diagram $D:[2,\kappa)\to\mathbf{HoGpd}$ by letting $D(\alpha)$ be free on $\alpha$ generators with action on morphisms the natural inclusions, denoted by $D^{\beta}_{\alpha}:D(\beta)\to D(\alpha)$. We have a cocone $A:D\to Z$ with $A_{\alpha}:D(\alpha)\to Z$ the natural inclusion of the vertex group. To see that these maps do constitute a cocone, we note that $y_{\alpha}^{\beta}$ is the unique component of a natural isomorphism $A_{\beta}\cong A_{\alpha}\circ D^{\beta}_{\alpha}$.
Definition 3.5. A graph of groups $\Gamma$ is given by: • A graph, i.e., a set $X$ of vertices, a set $Y$ of oriented edges, functions $s,t:Y\rightrightarrows X$, and an involution $\overline{(-)}:Y\to Y$ interchanging $s$ and $t$. • Groups $G_{x}$ and $G_{y}$ for $x\in X$ and $y\in Y$ equipped with monomorphisms $\mu_{y}:G_{y}\to G_{s(y)}$ such that $G_{y}=G_{\bar{y}}$. For simplicity, we assume that the groups $G_{x}$ are disjoint. For more on graphs of groups, see [6].
Definition 1 (Modeloid [1]) Let $M\subseteq F(\Sigma)$. $M$ is called a modeloid on $\Sigma$ if, and only if, it satisfies the following axioms: 1. Closure of composition: $f,g\in M\Rightarrow f\circ g\in M$ 2. Closure of taking inverses: $f\in M\Rightarrow f^{-1}\in M$ 3. Inclusion property: $f\in M$ and $A\subset dom(f)$ implies $f|_{A}\in M$ 4. Identity: $id_{\Sigma}\in M$
Definition 11 (categorical modeloid) Let $\mathbf{C}$ be a finite inverse category $\mathbf{C}$ with all zero elements. Then a categorical modeloid $M$ on $\mathbf{C}$ is such that $M\subseteq C$ satisfies the following axioms. 1. $a,b\in M\Rightarrow a\cdot b\in M$ 2. $a\in M\Rightarrow a^{-1}\in M$ 3. $\forall\,a\in C\,\forall b\in M:a\leq b\Rightarrow a\in M$ 4. $\forall\,\text{objects }X\in C:X\in M$
